  "prompt": "What are the situations where GDP increases but economic welfare don't?",
  "response": "There are several situations where GDP increases but economic welfare does not necessarily improve:\n\n1. Income Inequality\n- GDP growth concentrated among wealthy individuals\n- Limited benefit to lower and middle-income groups\n- Widening income disparity\n\n2. Environmental Degradation\n- Economic activities causing environmental damage\n- Increased production at the cost of natural resources\n- Long-term ecological consequences not reflected in GDP\n\n3. Negative Externalities\n- Growth from industries generating social costs\n- Increased pollution\n- Health-related expenses\n- Social disruptions\n\n4. Resource Extraction\n- Economic growth through unsustainable natural resource exploitation\n- Short-term gains without long-term economic sustainability\n\n5. Military/Defense Spending\n- GDP increase through military expenditures\n- Does not directly contribute to population's welfare\n- Resources diverted from social development\n\n6. Speculative Economic Activities\n- GDP growth through financial speculation\n- Limited real economic value creation\n- Potential financial instability\n\n7. Underground/Informal Economy\n- GDP growth not reflecting actual economic welfare\n- Unregulated economic activities\n- Limited social security and worker protections\n\n8. Healthcare Costs\n- Increased healthcare expenses contributing to GDP\n- Not necessarily indicating improved health outcomes\n\nThese scenarios demonstrate that GDP alone is an insufficient measure of economic well-being and societal progress.",
